## 5. THE OLD FORMULA VS. THE NEW FORMULA

### 5.1 The Old Formula (Experimental, 1798-Present)

```
G = F × r² / (m₁ × m₂)
```

Where F is the gravitational force measured between two known masses m₁ and m₂ separated by distance r.

This is a **physical measurement:**
- Requires a laboratory with sensitive equipment
- Subject to experimental error (22 ppm uncertainty)
- Different experiments yield different results (the G anomaly)
- Treats G as a fundamental property of nature

### 5.2 The New Formula (Mathematical Identity)

```
G = ℓ_P³ / (m_P × t_P²)
```

This is a **mathematical identity:**
- Requires no laboratory, no equipment, no experiment
- Has **zero mathematical uncertainty**
- Always yields the same result for given Planck values
- Reveals G as a unit conversion factor

### 5.3 The Fundamental Difference

| Aspect | Old G | New G |
|--------|-------|-------|
| Nature | Physical constant | Unit conversion factor |
| Origin | Measured in laboratory | Derived from Planck definitions |
| Uncertainty | 22 ppm (experimental) | Zero (mathematical identity) |
| In natural units | 6.67430 × 10⁻¹¹ | **1 (exactly)** |
| If the meter changes | G changes | G changes accordingly |
| If the second changes | G changes | G changes accordingly |
| If the kilogram changes | G changes | G changes accordingly |

The old G is a measurement of the Planck scale in human units.
The new G is the recognition that the Planck scale IS the natural unit system — and G is just the conversion.

